0is%20hot%20again.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20Wednesday%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bls.gov%2Fcpi%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Enews%20release%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20the%20Bureau%20of%20Labor%20Statistics%20said%20the%20consumer%20price%20index%20increased%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E3.5%25%20for%20the%2012%20months%20ending%20in%20March.%20The%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.investing.com%2Feconomic-calendar%2Fcpi-733%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eforecast%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20March's%20year-over-year%20increase%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bls.gov%2Fcpi%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ECPI%20%3C%2Fa%3Ewas%203.4%25%2C%20a%20higher%20rate%20than%20the%203.2%25%20increase%20or%20the%203.1%25%20increase%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Finflation-cpi-consumer-price-index-food-gas-housing-prices-february-2024-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EFebruary%3C%2Fa%3E%20or%20January%2C%20respectively.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20rate%20came%20in%20above%20the%20forecast%20and%20was%20higher%20than%20February's%20year-over-year%20change.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2F3Cv32%2F23%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Consumer%20price%20index%20inflation%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22500%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3ECPI%20increased%200.4%25%20in%20March%20from%20the%20preceding%20month%20%E2%80%94%20the%20same%20as%20the%200.4%25%20surge%20in%20February.%20That's%20also%20comparable%20to%20the%20forecast%20of%200.3%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECore%20CPI%2C%20which%20excludes%20volatile%20food%20and%20energy%20prices%2C%20increased%203.8%25%20year%20over%20year%20in%20March.%20That's%20above%20the%20forecast%20of%203.7%25%20and%20the%20same%20as%20February's%203.8%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECore%20CPI%20also%20rose%20by%200.4%25%20again.%20The%20expected%20increase%20was%200.3%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20index%20for%20shelter%20rose%20in%20March%2C%20as%20did%20the%20index%20for%20gasoline%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20news%20release%20from%20the%20BLS%20published%20on%20Wednesday%20said.%20%26quot%3BCombined%2C%20these%20two%20indexes%20contributed%20over%20half%20of%20the%20monthly%20increase%20in%20the%20index%20for%20all%20items.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20shelter%20index%20rose%200.4%25%20again%20from%20the%20preceding%20month.%20This%20index%20saw%20a%205.7%25%20rise%20year%20over%20year%20in%20March%2C%20matching%20the%205.7%25%20year-over-year%20increase%20in%20February.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERent%20of%20primary%20residence%20increased%205.7%25%20year%20over%20year%2C%20and%20owners'%20equivalent%20rent%20of%20primary%20residence%20rose%205.9%25%20year%20over%20year.%20Shelter%20contributed%20to%20the%20bulk%20of%20the%20overall%20increase%20in%20prices%20over%20the%20year.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEnergy%20saw%20a%20smaller%20month-over-month%20increase%20in%20March%2C%20with%20a%201.1%25%20increase%20from%20February%20to%20March%20compared%20with%20the%202.3%25%20increase%20in%20February.%20Energy%20didn't%20see%20another%20year-over-year%20decline.%20It%20actually%20rose%202.1%25%20after%20February's%20year-over-year%20decline%20of%201.9%25.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20gas%20index%20rose%201.7%25%20month%20over%20month%20after%20a%203.8%25%20increase.%20This%20index%20climbed%201.3%25%20for%20the%2012%20months%20ending%20March%20after%20a%20drop%20of%203.9%25%20for%20the%2012%20months%20ending%20February.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFood%20saw%20a%200.1%25%20increase%20month%20over%20month%2C%20and%20this%20index%20saw%20a%202.2%25%20increase%20year%20over%20year.%20The%20index%20for%20food%20away%20from%20home%20is%20high%20compared%20with%20food%20at%20home.%20Food%20away%20from%20home%20had%20a%20year-over-year%20increase%20of%204.2%25%20compared%20with%20food%20at%20home's%201.2%25%20rise.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EJulia%20Pollak%2C%20the%20chief%20economist%20at%20ZipRecruiter%2C%20told%20Business%20Insider%20the%20jobs%20report%20released%20on%20Friday%20was%20%26quot%3Bthe%20Fed's%20holy%20grail%3A%20strong%20job%20market%20with%20non-inflationary%20growth.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fjobs-wages-growth-in-march-unemployment-rate-labor-market-2024-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EUS%20added%20303%2C000%20jobs%20in%20March%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20a%20robust%20gain%20after%20the%20strong%20270%2C000%20gain%20in%20February.%20Pollak%20said%20the%20increases%20in%20both%20job%20growth%20and%20the%20workweek%2C%20along%20with%20the%20drop%20in%20the%20unemployment%20rate%2C%20were%20%26quot%3Ball%20good%20signs%20about%20the%20enduring%20strength%20of%20the%20labor%20market%20and%20its%20dynamism.%26quot%3B%20She%20also%20noted%20the%20slower%20wage%20growth%2C%20which%20she%20said%20was%20%26quot%3Bgood%20news%20for%20a%20Fed%20that's%20still%20battling%20inflation.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAverage%20hourly%20earnings%20increased%204.1%25%20year%20over%20year%20to%20%2434.69%20an%20hour%20in%20March%2C%20which%20fell%20short%20of%20the%204.3%25%20year-over-year%20increase%20in%20February.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20is%20a%20developing%20story.%20Please%20check%20back%20for%20updates.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Finflation-cpi-food-energy-gas-prices-consumer-price-index-2024-4%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1712752745000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F661580e03f923f7dab05f76a%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Finflation-cpi-food-energy-gas-prices-consumer-price-index-2024-4%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Newly%20released%20data%20from%20the%20consumer%20price%20index%20shows%20inflat